|  | O\_{\theta,\vartheta}(x,y)=\vartheta(\theta(x)+\theta(y)) |  |

is an overlap function. The commutativity, continuity and monotonicity are obvious.

Note that for each x,y\in[0,1], \theta(x)+\theta(y)\in[2\theta(1),+\infty] since \theta is non-increasing and continuous. It follows from (b) and (iii) that \vartheta(\theta(x)+\theta(y))=0 if and only if \theta(x)+\theta(y)=+\infty if and only if xy=0. Moreover, it follows from (c) and (iv) that \vartheta(\theta(x)+\theta(y))=1 if and only if \theta(x)+\theta(y)=2\theta(1) if and only if xy=1.

Therefore, by Definition 2.1 the bivariate function O\_{\theta,\vartheta} is an overlap function.

The following proposition presents the conditions what \vartheta needs to satisfy when O\_{\theta,\vartheta}(x,y)=\vartheta(\theta(x)+\theta(y)) is an overlap function.

###### Proposition 2.3.

Let \theta:[0,1]\rightarrow[0,+\infty] be a function with both \theta(x^{-}) and \theta(x^{+}) existing for every x\in[0,1] and \vartheta:[0,+\infty]\rightarrow[-\infty,+\infty] be a function. If the bivariate function O\_{\theta,\vartheta}:[0,1]^{2}\rightarrow[0,1] given by

|  |  |  |
| --- | --- | --- |
|  | O\_{\theta,\vartheta}(x,y)=\vartheta(\theta(x)+\theta(y)) |  |

is an overlap function then the following three statements hold:

* (a)

  \vartheta is continuous and non-increasing in [2\theta(1),+\infty];
* (b)

  \vartheta(x)=0 with x\in[2\theta(1),+\infty] if and only if x=+\infty;
* (c)

  \vartheta(x)=1 with x\in[2\theta(1),+\infty] if and only if x=2\theta(1).

Proof.
Suppose that the bivariate function O\_{\theta,\vartheta} is an overlap function.
Then from Proposition 2.2 (i) and (ii), \theta(x)+\theta(y)\in[2\theta(1),+\infty] for each x,y\in[0,1].

(a) If \vartheta is not continuous in [2\theta(1),+\infty], then O\_{\theta,\vartheta}(x,y)=\vartheta(\theta(x)+\theta(y)) is not continuous, a contradiction.

From Proposition 2.2 (ii), \theta(y)\geq\theta(z) for each x,y,z\in[0,1] with y<z. Then \vartheta(\theta(x)+\theta(y))\leq\vartheta(\theta(x)+\theta(z)) since O\_{\theta,\vartheta} is non-decreasing. Therefore, \vartheta is non-increasing in [2\theta(1),+\infty].

(b) If \vartheta(x)=0 with x\in[2\theta(1),+\infty], then from Proposition 2.2 (i) there exist y,z\in[0,1] such that x=\theta(y)+\theta(z). Hence \vartheta(\theta(y)+\theta(z))=\vartheta(x)=0. From Definition 2.1 (O2), yz=0. Thus from Proposition 2.2 (iii), x=\theta(y)+\theta(z)=+\infty.

Conversely, \vartheta(+\infty)=\vartheta(2\theta(0))=0 from Proposition 2.2 (iii).

(c) If \vartheta(x)=1 with x\in[2\theta(1),+\infty], then from Proposition 2.2 (i) there exist y,z\in[0,1] such that x=\theta(y)+\theta(z). Hence \vartheta(x)=\vartheta(\theta(y)+\theta(z))=1. From Definition 2.1 (O3), yz=1. Thus x=\theta(y)+\theta(z)=2\theta(1).

The converse implication, \vartheta(x)=\vartheta(2\theta(1))=1 by Definition 2.1 (O3).

Notice that from Proposition 2.3, the values of the function \vartheta:[0,+\infty]\rightarrow[-\infty,+\infty] in [0,2\theta(1)) have no influence on the overlap function O\_{\theta,\vartheta}. Therefore, we only need to consider the values of the function \vartheta:[0,+\infty]\rightarrow[-\infty,+\infty] in [2\theta(1),+\infty] when we investigate the additive generator pair (\theta,\vartheta) of the overlap function O\_{\theta,\vartheta}.

The following theorem connects Propositions 2.2 with 2.3.

###### Theorem 2.1.

Let \theta:[0,1]\rightarrow[0,+\infty] be a function with both \theta(x^{-}) and \theta(x^{+}) existing for every x\in[0,1] and \vartheta:[0,+\infty]\rightarrow[-\infty,+\infty] be a function. Then the bivariate function O\_{\theta,\vartheta}:[0,1]^{2}\rightarrow[0,1] given by

|  |  |  |
| --- | --- | --- |
|  | O\_{\theta,\vartheta}(x,y)=\vartheta(\theta(x)+\theta(y)) |  |

is an overlap function if and only if the following statements hold:

* (1)

  \theta is continuous and non-increasing;
* (2)

  \vartheta is continuous and non-increasing in [2\theta(1),+\infty];
* (3)

  \theta(x)=+\infty if and only if x=0;
* (4)

  \vartheta(x)=0 with x\in[2\theta(1),+\infty] if and only if x=+\infty;
* (5)

  For a given a\in[0,+\infty), the following two conditions are equivalent:
  (i) \theta(x)=\frac{a}{2} if and only if x=1;
  (ii) \vartheta(x)=1 with x\in[a,+\infty] if and only if x=a.